english:
  title: A Poem Composed of Joined Lines at Jangnyeon Temple on Gaegol Mountain
  author: Im Yu-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Walking on and on in search of natural beauty, I forget my worldly cares.
    How fine it is to climb the mountain and stand by the water.
    The chaotic waterfalls and flying streams cry out with splashing sound.
    Layered peaks and stacked ridges rise in wild profusion.
    Mist-light shimmers soft; even on clear days the mountain stays moist.
    The mountain's hue grows hazy; in rain, it becomes even stranger and more wondrous.
    Who among us can truly appreciate this moment and this scene?
    Only the master of Red Lotus Temple, the venerable Bigyun—surely he alone.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This poem is composed entirely of 'joined lines' (集句), where each line or couplet is drawn from the works of different Tang and Song Chinese poets, as indicated by the poet names in parentheses in the original. This was a sophisticated literary game among East Asian literati.
  - key: ''
    value: Red Lotus Temple (紅蓮社) and its master Bigyun (碧雲師) likely refer to a specific Buddhist temple and its abbot known to the author, establishing a spiritual connection between the natural beauty described and enlightened appreciation of it.
